Your Honor,

I stand before this honorable court to take full responsibility for my actions and express my deep regrets for the offense I committed. On the day in question, I made an impulsive decision to test the speed capabilities of my new car. It was a reckless act that not only endangered my own life but also posed a serious threat to the safety of those around me. I understand the gravity of my actions and the potential harm that could have occurred.

I would like to acknowledge that I failed to respond to the Notice of Intended Prosecution (NIP) due to my negligence in checking my mail regularly. However, I assure the court that if I had seen the notice, I would have promptly responded to it. I wish to express my sincerest apologies for this failure to comply with the necessary legal procedures.

In regards to my driving record, I must admit that I have received penalty points from three previous speeding incidents on my license. I am deeply remorseful for these past offenses and have since reflected upon my behavior. I want to assure the court that, aside from these driving offenses, I have no other record of criminal activity.

Furthermore, I feel it is important to disclose that I have been diagnosed with ADHD. While this does not excuse my actions, I believe it is crucial for the court to understand that this condition may have influenced my impulsive decision-making process. However, I fully acknowledge that it does not absolve me of my responsibility and the consequences that accompany my actions.

I would like to express my utmost regret for the harm I have caused and the disregard I have shown for traffic laws. I am committed to learning from this experience and making the necessary changes to become a responsible and law-abiding citizen. I understand the severity of my actions and the potential risks posed by my behavior, and I am genuinely remorseful for my actions.

Thank you for your attention to this matter, and I humbly request the court's leniency as I work towards bettering myself and making amends for my mistakes.

Respectfully,
Robert Chapman

